<paragraph blockId="54.[151,1436,1866,2036]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">
Only one species of this relatively large genus of 25 species occurs in 
<collectingCountry box="[961,1057,1902,1928]" name="Ecuador" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
. Adults are small and are usually mostly red, rarely with blue on head and tip of abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[822,909,1938,1965]" captionStart="FIGURE 27" captionStartId="55.[151,250,786,811]" captionTargetBox="[340,1247,181,767]" captionTargetId="figure@55.[340,1247,181,767]" captionTargetPageId="55" captionText="FIGURE 27. Oxyagrion tennesseni ♂, ECUADOR, Napo Prov., small stream, &lt;1 km E of Río Sardinas Grande, 24 x 2013; photo K. J. Tennessen." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3335741/files/figure.png" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Fig. 27</figureCitation>
). See 
<bibRefCitation author="Mauffray, W. F." box="[981,1170,1938,1965]" pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="165 - 170" refId="ref196240" refString="Mauffray, W. F. (1999) Oxyagrion tennesseni spec. nov. from Ecuador (Zygoptera: Coenagrionidae). Odonatologica, 28 (2), 165 - 170." type="journal article" year="1999">Mauffray (1999)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="von Ellenrieder, N. &amp; Lozano, F." pageId="54" pageNumber="55" pagination="95 - 113" refId="ref205262" refString="von Ellenrieder, N. &amp; Lozano, F. (2008) Blues for the red Oxyagrion: a redefinition of the genera Acanthagrion and Oxyagrion (Odonata: Coenagrionidae). International Journal of Odonatology, 11 (1), 95 - 113. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 13887890.2008.9748315" type="journal article" year="2008">von Ellenrieder &amp; Lozano (2008)</bibRefCitation>
for identification and diagnoses. Habitat in 
<collectingCountry box="[810,903,1974,2000]" name="Ecuador" pageId="54" pageNumber="55">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
is mainly small seeps and slow stream edges at high elevations.
</paragraph>
